"This book begins with the invocation of some rural deities, and a cowmpliment to Augustus: after which Virgil direets him- self to Mcenas, and enters on his subject. He lays down rales for the breeding and managemment of horses, oxen, shieep, goats, and dogs; and interweaves several pleasant de- seriptions of a chariot-race, of the battle of the bulls, of the force of love, and of the Seythian winter. In the latter part of the book, he relates the diseases incident to cattle; and ends with the deseription of a fatzl murrain that formerly"